Tech leaders are racing to adopt todayРђЎs AI tools and envisioning ways to capitalize on tomorrowРђЎs quantum computers. But cybercriminals are a few steps ahead. This month, theNET examines ways to make the most of AI agents while augmenting security with AI-enhanced solutions and safeguarding data with post-quantum cryptography. Combating AI-powered threats What's new: Cybercriminals are tapping into AI to speed development of large, sophisticated threats Рђћ from huge DDoS attacks to convincing deepfake messages. Why it matters: Organizations need AI to defeat AI. More proactive, AI-enhanced security is crucial for defending against the latest threats. Article (8 min read) Boosting government efficiency with AI agents WhatРђЎs new: Government agencies are eager to adopt AI agents to address todayРђЎs strict mandates to streamline operations and cut costs. Why it matters: Preparing for technical change and implementing guardrails will be critical for maximizing gains and addressing serious security risks.┬а Article (7 min read) Post-quantum game plan WhatРђЎs new: Attackers are poised to use quantum computing to break todayРђЎs cryptographic systems Рђћ and theyРђЎre already harvesting data. Why it matters: To future-proof organizations, tech leaders need to build a game plan for post-quantum cryptography now.
